general.headline: CEO Elect at Coles Group
general.description: Youngest ever CEO of a FTSE 100 Company and former director of Metcash, Coles, Asda, Pacific Equity Partners and ITV. Entrepreneurial leader who has successfully grown shareholder value in multi billion dollar retail and media companies in both the UK and Australia. Expertise includes food retail turnarounds, new store formats, buying & marketing, product development, internet, cost reduction & cash flow improvement, M&A, public markets, private equity and advisory.

jobs.description:
The Coles team has been proudly serving Australia for over 100 years. There are now
      more than 110,00 team members working in 2500+ retail outlets, 21 distribution
      centres, and a store support centre to deliver more than 21 million customer
      transactions every week in the food, beverage and fuel markets. "Good things are
      
      happening @ Coles!"

The Metcash purpose is to support & grow the number of Successful Independent Retailers in Australia, many of whom are the Heart & Soul of their communities. By becoming a world class wholesaler and retail services partner MTS helps deliver "the Best Store in Town". MTS has sales of $9Bn and owns the Foodland brand, manages the IGA supermarkets (www.iga.com.au) & Campbells wholesale brands, and provides the leading "1 stop shop" food & beverage service to retailers including 7-Eleven, BP and  Foodworks. Having joined the Metcash team in 2015 and launched the "Working Smarter" program shareholder value more than doubled despite the most competitive conditions ever experienced in Australia.

Providing advisory services to FMCG, retail, media and private equity organisations in
      
      Europe, Asia and the USA

Member of PEP's investment and operating committees responsible for screening up to 100 deals per annum and adding value (including group buying synergies) to a diverse portfolio of companies in the consumer goods, industrial and financial services sectors.  Chairman of former PEP portfolio companies Redgroup Retail & Godfreys. 

Lead advisor and business plan architect for the Wesfarmers/PEP/Permira consortium on its bid for Coles Group - Australia's largest corporate takeover.

Coles is the second largest retailer and private employer in Australia. Brands include Coles Supermarkets, Coles/Shell Express Service Stations, Liquorland & Vintage Cellars Liquor Stores, and Coles Online. 
- Increased comp store sales from lowest in the industry to the highest
- Delivered double digit EBIT and shareholder value growth 
- Reduced central costs
- Introduced new store format focused on fresh foods, Australia's first self scanning checkouts, and three tier house brand strategy

Established Europe's largest retailer of electric vehicles through the iconic "G-Wiz".
      First vehicle retailer to sell online without showrooms & provide mobile servicing.
      Company has won over 50 environmental and other awards including BT Start Up Of
      
      The Year.

Carlton PLC, a FTSE 100 company, owned ITV, the UK's largest commercial TV broadcaster and producer, and Technicolor, the California based leading global provider of film, dvd and digital services to the entertainment industry including Disney, Warner Bros, Microsoft, cinemas and consumers. Increased shareholder value by divesting non-core businesses, investing in production and digital capabilities, and facilitating the consolidation of ITV which at the time was based around regional franchises.

Responsibilities included buying, merchandising, marketing, advertising, own brand development, new store development & refurbishments, space management, product pricing and promotions, major change initiatives.
Achievements included being part of team that grew profits, market share and brand awareness for 6 consecutive years despite 4 full range supermarket competitors and the emergence of 3 European limited assortment discounters    
Developed and implemented plans to:
- grow own brand share from lowest in the in the UK to the highest
- introduce category management and significantly reduce grocery space to facilitate growth in fresh foods and clothing
- reduce costs and build time of new store and renewal program

general.headline: Director - Demerger Program at Coles
general.description:
I am a highly experienced business professional who has worked as part of the senior leadership team at Coles for over six years. 

There’s no average day for me as I manage my own expectations and have done away with to-do lists. This allows me to focus on working closely with my team and supporting them to prioritise what needs to be done while completing my own projects in between. 

Throughout my working career I’ve held positions in companies large, small, profitable and even not so profitable which has given me experience at all ends of the spectrum. I work best with tangible businesses where I can provide real solutions and drive change end-to-end, from head office to store level. 

I have memories of shopping at Coles while growing up and after spending time in the UK I came back to Australia to pursue a senior position in the Coles leadership team. 

As Coles is a company that encourages the opportunity to build a diverse and fulfilling career and embraces the value that finance can contribute to driving the performance of the business, I have had the opportunity to lead and drive change both in our Stores (#goteamvic)  for our customers and also at our Store Support Centre. I work hard to instil a sense of pride into the business and am committed to ensuring that we work to provide value to every customer. 

Areas of great importance to me are:

Providing real value to families by reducing the cost of their weekly shop

Creating careers full of diverse opportunities for my team

Ensuring that food quality is of utmost importance in all stores

Providing a safe and empowering environment for our team members

Using the power of Coles to have a positive impact on the Australian economy and food industry

I am a People & Culture expert with significant experience coaching and leading through change.

jobs.description:
As part of the Financial Services function at Coles, I partner with leaders to provide effective HR advice and consultation. Key responsibilities include:

• Develop, communicate, and implement the People Strategy 
• Enable the Financial Services function to recruit, develop, and motivate our team members
• Support our leaders to develop and embed our desired culture, values, and behaviours
• Administer the Performance Management process
• Support and coach leaders to manage employee disputes and other issues

As part of the People & Organisation team I focused on performance improvement through the lens of Human Resources, with particular interest in Change Management and Leadership Development. 

My work centered on four main areas: 
 
• Organisational Capability & Effectiveness
• Talent Management & Workforce Optimisation
• Human Resource Enablement
• Program and Organisational Change

Working within the Human Resources department, my primary function was as the e-Recruitment Coordinator.

In this role, I was the superuser for the University's e-recruitment system, PageUp. My responsibilities included:

- day-to-day maintenance of the system
- support person for user queries
- updating advertising on internal and external job databases
- liaison between the university and central PageUp support

My role also included training HR staff on use of the PageUp system.

As an administrator within the HR team, I was also responsible for day-to-day administrative duties around the office.

Interacted with C-Level management to ensure both staff and client welfare within the bank.

Liaised with senior management to discuss ways to improve company procedures that aligned with standards of professionalism.

Built and developed relationships with external clients to ensure excellent service levels.

Following my college career, I moved to Europe to play professional basketball. Played in various countries including Morocco, Spain, and England. This experience developed my understanding of teamwork and leadership in unique and pressurised situations. 

Highlights included leading my team, Raja Casablanca, to the top of the domestic league and final of the Throne Cup, and being a part of the first Leicester Riders team to reach the playoffs in 4 years.

general.headline: CEO at Survivors & Mates Support Network (SAMSN)
general.description:
SAMSN is an ngo working to increase public awareness of the effects that child sexual abuse can have on men in their adult lives.
 
SAMSN is a survivor focused and survivor driven charity that provides resources to male survivors of childhood sexual abuse to help them deal with the past and live a full and rewarding life.

We employ psychologists and social workers who have experience working with male survivors to facilitate support groups and workshops for men and their families. Our groups and workshops provide practical and emotional support to men and their families as we work to build a caring, non-judgemental and inclusive community. 

We advocate on behalf of male survivors to dispel the myths and provide information to make it easier for men to disclose and seek the help they need.

Our mission is to build an Australia-wide support network so that no man experiencing the negative impacts of childhood sexual abuse has to suffer in shame, silence or isolation.

Any man who has struggled with the effects of child sexual assault should know it was not his fault and that healing and recovery is possible. Regardless of his ethnicity, sexual orientation, age, or religion, any man across Australia can contact SAMSN for support.

Billy is an experienced management consultant, with core expertise in business modelling and planning. Billy has worked with organisations across a broad range of industries and specialises in advising organisations in the human services sector, in particular, those transitioning to the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS).

jobs.jobTitle: Governance Committee Member and Lead NDIS Consultant
jobs.description:
Ready4 is the first point of contact for all ACT community sector organisations preparing their transition to the NDIS. Beyond NDIS, Ready4 also supports the broader human services industry in the ACT for inter-organisational partnership or collaboration initiatives. Funded by ACT and Commonwealth governments, Ready4 is a consortium between National Disability Services, ACT Council of Social Services and RSM.

Billy is one of three members of the Ready4 Governance Committee and leads Ready4's NDIS consultancy services including one-on-one consultancy that is accessible to ACT organisations through an application process and is free of charge.

Visit Ready4 website (www.ready4.org.au) for latest resources and information on NDIS and collaboration. You can also view and book upcoming workshops, seminars and exhibitions on the website.

As a senior manager and team leader, Billy built a management consulting team of 7 from the ground up. Billy's team developed expertise in helping organisations prepare for and transition to the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS). Since the beginning of the roll-out of the NDIS, Billy led and coordinated over 60 business transition and transformation projects with disability and human service providers in the ACT, NSW and Victoria.

Apart from the human services industry, Billy and his team also advised and provided management consulting services to organisations in health, energy, IT, property, manufacturing and the public sector.

general.headline: General Manager at Insurance & Care NSW (icare)
general.description:
General Manager of Health & Community Engagement at icare - collaborative leader, passionate and socially innovative health reformer.

icare is the largest general insurance provider in Australia and proudly delivers insurance and care services to the NSW community. 

Eugene is the General Manager of Health and Community Engagement at icare. In this role, he uses his expertise in partnering business and community to drive icare’s innovation in partnership agenda. Through this initiative, icare aspires to prevent injury or improve recovery rates for injured people..

He is a strong advocate of challenging convention and disrupting the status quo in the pursuit of developing socially innovative solutions to address deep-rooted problems with disadvantage. Continually exhorting community, government, non-government and business to work together collectively and collaboratively to establish a flourishing ecosystem supporting the wellbeing of all. 

Starting his career back in 1979 as a mental health nurse, he has spent almost 4 decades in various roles in government health and social services in the UK and Australia, on a mission to tackle the ‘wicked’ problems affecting vulnerable people, families and communities. In 1998, he joint-led a project that reduced suicide rates by 40% in south west London.

A current member of the Mental Health Community Advisory Council, Eugene adds his extensive expertise to the 18 member council to highlight issues that affect the mental health and wellbeing of the people of NSW. 

Eugene is believer in empowering vulnerable communities to design their own solutions, an influencer in encouraging experimentation and exploration of new approaches to the delivery of services supporting the community. In 2013, he co-designed and delivered The Collective NSW. The aim of the Collective is to better connect community, government, non-government and business to break the cycle of disadvantage.

jobs.description:
icare aims to be a centre of excellence for providing person-centric insurance services, return to work solutions, and care for people who have been severely injured in the workplace or on the road. Based on our assets ($30bn) and liabilities ($26bn), icare is the largest general insurance service provider in Australia. 

Using his expertise in partnering business with community, Eugene is driving the innovation agenda at icare. He is continually advocating for research to inform the design of solutions, and communities being empowered to design the solutions they need. 

Ufirst, an initiative of icare, brings together participants from the health system and the community to co-design better solutions to improve injury prevention and worker recovery.

Ufirst seeks to improve workers’ wellbeing at work, enhance timely and evidence-based treatment for injured workers, and support better health, social and economic outcomes for injured workers disconnected from work.

As District Director of Family & Community Services NSW, Eugene played an instrumental role in co-designing and delivering The Collective NSW.  The aim of the Collective is to better connect community, government, non-government and business to break the cycle of disadvantage.  

Responsible for more than 1,000 full-time equivalents and an operational budget of $100m, Eugene created the Community Government partnership framework known as The Collective NSW, and designed and implemented an integrated service model for Northern Sydney.

jobs.companyName: NSW Department of Family & Community Services
jobs.description:
Lead and manage service delivery in child protection, social housing, disability and
      
      home care.

As Regional Director, Eugene led the growth and delivery of client-centred services in the areas of child protection, social housing, disability and home care.  Providing leadership for the region and acting as an ambassador for ADHC with local stakeholders, Eugene managed 750 full time equivalents and an operating budget of $30m.  

Eugene was formally accountable for the performance of the Northern Sydney region, and he managed the delivery and commissioning of support services to people with a disability through a range of services.

jobs.companyName: Ageing, Disability and Home  Care, Department of Human Services NSW
jobs.description:
As Deputy Director or Ageing, Disability and Home Care for the northern region, I was instrumental in the development of a model which came to be known as Communities Around Kids. This model is centred around providing services and support to customers based on the needs of the carer and those in their care.  

Managing 250 full time equivalents and an operating budget of $20m, Eugene managed the delivery of support services, commissioned over 300 non-government organisations to deliver support services, and worked in partnership with other human service agencies.  Furthermore, he funded and implemented emergency response services, and delivered innovative projects to reduce the risk of parents relinquishing the care of their child.

As Associate Director, Eugene led and drove the management and implementation of a range of strategies and health policies relating to mental health, drugs and alcohol, and workforce in NSW.  In charge of 60 full-time equivalents and an operational budget of $1.9m, Eugene managed the consultation for the new Mental Health Act, supported the Director General of the Cabinet Office, and led a significant recruitment campaign for senior specialists to build capacity in rural areas.  Finally, Eugene developed and implement results based performance scorecards for area health services, and led the development of new systems and policies.

As Senior Policy Advisor to the Minister of Health, Eugene was directly involved in inter-agency mental health reform. This included consultation for the new mental health legislation.  Eugene was responsible for providing policy advice in the run up to the 2006 NSW State Government budget, in which he directly worked with the NSW Minister for Health, and the Minister assisting them.

Provided leadership in taking mental health services through significant change and
      
      improvement.

jobs.description:
NDS is the national industry association for disability services, representing over 800 non- government organisations. Collectively, our members operate several thousand services for Australians with all types of disability. NDS’s members range in size from small support groups to large multi-service organisations, and are located in every State and Territory across Australia. 

In Victoria, our members employ over 8,000 people and are supported by countless volunteers in delivering vital services. 

As State Manager, I lead a team dedicated to improving the disability service system to ensure it better supports people with disability, families and carers. 

We provide high quality information and support to our member organisations in relation to service delivery, management, governance and operations; initiate research and document key issues facing the local disability field; contribute to development of the national disability policy agenda, and represent NDS and the interests of our members in our advocacy and engagement with government and and other bodies.

jobs.description:
Our Vision

“Community Support Services, to help people stay independent”

We achieve our Vision by:

Providing a range of community support services on the Northern Beaches and in Northern Sydney to assist people to remain in their own homes and be independent.

Identifying and developing opportunities to expand our services and operations in complementary areas to ensure sustainability 

Ensuring we operate in accordance with best practice.

As CEO, I lead a talented group of over 200 Professionals, Aged Care Workers, Tradesmen and Volunteers who work hard for the interests of the aged residents on the Northern Beaches of Sydney.  We are delivering a progressive and outcome focussed plan for our Seniors to become self reliant, independent, healthy and happy. It is a great honour to serve our community.

In this role, I spearheaded and implemented national health projects for Better Health Care Connections under the Federal Government Living Longer, Living Better initiative using PRINCE2®. Some of the major projects I developed include launching a risk management tool, managing client assessment and validation for an IT project in collaboration with IT project managers. I was also involved in projects with Health Workforce Australia and Telecare. I also served as project lead and supervised cross-functional project teams for care facility projects, including Sunshine Coast Post Discharge Transitional Care for the Elderly, SA Ambulance & GP Stay @ Home Care, SESLHD Strength & Balance Training, and SWSLHD Campbelltown Hospital Settling at Home Service. I exceeded 100% of target for total client referrals and met all KPIs.

I provided strategic leadership to PM Works in initiating complex health projects. I counseled project managers and clients on health-related issues, including Cochlear. I wrote succession plans, improved company processes through consultation with the Australian Public Service. As a company leader, I mentored & coached diverse teams, including junior Project Managers. I interfaced with BD Manager on business development, project management, and client satisfaction. 

While at PM Works, I oversaw $3.8M tender to Australian Government (DoHA) for personally controlled electronic health record (PCEHR).

I also oversaw programs for 15 Aged Care Facilities in Eastern Sydney.

I increased revenue every year for seven years. My division was the first accredited division out of 37 divisions statewide.  In this position, I also designed process for Access to Allied Psychologists Program (ATAPs) funded by the Federal government. I also acted as External Change Manager for the St. Vincent's Hospital PCEHR project.

Managed the business activity of the company, attended board meetings, managed finances, P&L, Balance Sheet, Annual Audits, Reporting, Administration, Salary Packaging, and ATO Private Rulings.

In my role with the Royal Australian Navy, I managed the School of Underwater Medicine and oversaw corporate management functions for Maritime Headquarters. I supervised the Balmoral Naval Hospital, the RAN Hospital as a member of the Hospital Management Board. I was involved in Rescue at Sea missions during the Sydney to Hobart race. At Maritime Headquarters I managed a budget of $75M and improved a multi-million dollar business planning model. I also supervised 12 direct reports and 66 staff at the hospital and mentored personnel and assessed performance of non commissioned officers and civilians in the hospital. 

An interesting and exciting career in the Navy Medical Branch. The RAN was a great opportunity to develop good leadership skills and take advantage of the extensive education and training. I would definitely recommend the military for any young person seeking a rewarding and satisfying career.

general.headline: CEO at Thrive365
general.description:
As a leader in the Disability Services sector with intricate knowledge and expertise in the NDIS, I have continuously delivered successful strategic and tactical outcomes for disability services. 

As a parent, carer and disability services professional, I’ve experienced service delivery first hand as both a consumer and at the forefront of the transition to the National Disability Insurance Scheme.

With this 360-degree view of the challenges and opportunities that lay ahead for people and services, it’s my goal with Thrive365 to ensure that the individual always remains the focus of the provision of services.

We work in a transparent partnership with every individual to ensure their needs are met in a way that allows them to thrive, each and every day.

jobs.description:
Disability Support with a Difference.

At Thrive365, we’re all about choice and partnership.
We believe you should be able to choose how your NDIS funding is spent. 
We believe you should be able to choose the staff who support you and this means everyone from your support coordinator to your therapist or gardener. 
We believe that the best support comes from working in partnership. 
And we believe you should have control over your life so you can truly thrive.

How we work
We support your right to choice.
A combination of access to specialist NDIS support staff and our online system allows you to self-manage as much or as little of your support service as you choose.

We work in partnership with you.
It’s our goal to build a true partnership with you. Listening, learning and working together in collaboration so you can thrive. For us, this is at the heart of successful disability support delivery.

We won’t hide anything from you.
We know that any true partnership is based on transparency and trust. From your case notes to every detail on how your funding has been spent, you’ll always have full access to your life with us.

It’s time to thrive.

Make the most of every day. Call us to find out how you can Thrive365.

jobs.jobTitle: NDIS Readiness Manager | Project Manager | NDIS Policy Officer | Stakeholder & Community Engagement
jobs.description:
Engaged in Australia’s peak body for non-government disability service organisations to manage the Victorian NDIS Readiness network and provide support to NDS offices, communities and advisory committees. Using my extensive networks and knowledge of key strategic issues on NDIA transition, I engaged industry stakeholders to work towards understanding and achieving unified goals. I successfully lobbied state Government for funding and facilitated communications with industry CEOs.

KEY SUCCESSES:
PROJECT AND POLICY | Entrusted to manage key projects and write policies providing support NDS service providers in the NDIA transition in change management and the implementation of collaborative frameworks. 

NDIS BARWON IMPLEMENTATION GROUP | Refocused the NDIS Barwon Implementation Group by improving communication initiatives with service providers to achieve understanding of different perspectives and information sharing across the disability service.

PRESENTATION AND FACILITATION | Proactively promoted the NDIS Organisational Readiness Toolkit through presentations and facilitation of events to educate, empower and support providers in the delivery of the NDIS. Facilitated industry CEO meetings and lobbied in state Government to achieve funding required.

Entrusted to plan and implement the NDIS Readiness Plan for Victoria in a standalone role requiring significant research and analysis into organisational service provisions for alignment with NDIS Readiness Plan milestones and requirements. Key aspects I managed included quality management, change management, strategic stakeholder engagement, service delivery and alignment with other sector reforms.

PROJECT PLANNING | Developed full scale project plans using  best practice project management and change management principles, driving the direction of each stage of the plan and implementing a change management framework across the organisation.

COMMUNICATION | Engaged with stakeholders across multiple communication channels including market research reports, facilitating workshops and information sessions, visual documentation and presentations. Audiences included advocacy groups, government representatives, internal executives and clients. 

NDIS RESEARCH AND ANALYSIS | Undertook extensive and complex research into NDIS requirements, disability sector reforms, Wesley Mission service offerings, funding allocations and request formats, contributing to the success in delivering on overall project objectives.

As Kinship Case Manager for Wesley Mission Victoria, I was responsible for effectively
      
      managing kinship care placements to ensure their ongoing stability.

general.headline: Amalgamation Transaction and Strategic Business Development consultant to the Not-for-Profit sector
general.company: Centigrowth, a consulting business supporting the Not-for-Profit sector
general.school: Law, Economics, Governance & Commercial Real Estate
general.description:
Today many Organisations are under increasing pressure from a range of stakeholders to upscale; whether that translates to consolidating with like-minded, merging, an acquisition or amalgamation - the issues and processes are similar.

I have a significant amount of recent experience in overseeing Amalgamation transactions in the Not-for-Profit sector having engaged in 19 quite different transactions over the past five years. In the ordinary course I tailor a staged process to assist parties through the Amalgamation transaction  and subsequent Integration and Optimisation phases;  with supporting communication matrix’s and the like.

My more general field of expertise is strategic business development and growth in the Community sector. I help lift strategic plans from the white board and pragmatically go about the process of implementation. I make the cold calls, follow up leads, make introductions and work with teams to develop relationships and opportunity. 

More generally, my background is as a proven business proprietor and organisational leader with expertise in developing and driving change. I have a demonstrated capacity to lead teams of independent Professionals, as well as a diverse range of support staff, to achieve strategic outcomes in both an organisational and altruistic sense.

In summary I have extensive experience in:-

* Mergers, takeovers and amalgamations
* Strategic business development and growth
* Developing new markets and sourcing new clients
* Public speaking & event management 
* Complex problem solving
* Day to day applications of Corporate Governance

I provide a no obligation free initial consultation to any Organisation, CEO or director seeking advice on how I may be able to add value to your Organisation. Please email me at stevedixon@centigrowth.com or call or text my mobile on 0407 589 461 to arrange a mutually convenient time to teleconference.

jobs.jobTitle: Group Executive Manager, Business and Partnership Development
jobs.description:
I was initially engaged as a business development consultant to the Community Solutions Group and after 6 months was invited to work full time as a Group Executive Manager to oversee the group’s ambitious growth portfolio. My role was to implement the business development aspects of its strategic plan which was largely achieved through Amalgamations and business development with like-minded service providers working primarily in the Community Sector.

In 2010 the Community Solutions Group had a turnover of $16m p.a. and employed FTE of 265 people. By October, 2013 its turnover was $32m and it employed 495 people. I was then part of the initial team that initiated an Amalgamation with the Endeavour Foundation which is likely to be finalised in the near future. This upscale is part of Endeavour Foundations strategy to develop capacity across a National footprint to meet the challenges of the National Disability Insurance Scheme. It was also a quantum leap in Community Solutions long term sustainability.

jobs.description:
COTA (Council on the Ageing) Queensland - advancing the rights, needs and futures of people as we age.

COTA Queensland is a statewide not for profit organisation giving older Queenslanders a voice on issues that affect them.

We work in partnership with older Queenslanders and governments to create an Age Friendly Queensland.

As the State’s Seniors Peak organisation, COTA Queensland works collaboratively to advance the rights, needs and interests of older people.

Our members and stakeholders are individuals aged 50 years and over, and organisations that support people as they age.  We work with consumers, self-help and special interest groups as well as federal, state and local government, and non- government organisations to achieve the best outcomes for people as they age.

We value the principles of partnership, integrity, respect and inclusion.

What we do: 

Provide policy and advice to governments and organisations.
Provide older people with information which enables them to make informed choices and take action on their behalf.
Promote and engage in research which is of interest and concern to older people.
Advocate on behalf of older people, giving priority to those suffering injustice, discrimination, disadvantage or disability.
Work in partnership with older Queenslanders to inform COTA Queensland’s policy and advocacy work.

www.cotaqld.org.au

Check out Soundcloud and type in 'Radio Cota" to listen to the latest Podcast. Click "LIKE".

general.headline: Mental Health Consultant ~ Entrepreneur ~ Frustrated Artist
general.description:
About Foundation 180 (formerly International Community Advocates)

Foundation 180 is a not-for-profit organisation dedicated to supporting children and families devastated by abuse, family violence, neglect, poverty, homelessness, mental health issues and long-term unemployment.

We have over recent years founded  a number of innovative gap provision services to children, young people and their families. Our aim: to provide a holistic approach to family support which meets needs where other organisations can not. Our focus: children at risk or experiencing violence, homelessness and/or abuse. Through our projects we work closely with many agencies providing housing and case management to women and children fleeing domestic and family violence.

Many sweeping changes have occurred in our sector over the past months and our organisation is watching closely as the new landscape begins to unfurl around us. Our intensive projects providing NEW clothing, toiletries, kitchenware, linen, household items, mattresses, toys and refurbished computers to dv/fv and trauma victims and the our local hospitals, have now been passed over to other charities or churches who are continuing this much needed work. 

Our current focus:

Training  – We provide education to professionals and front line workers around complex issues such as :Trauma, Dissociative Disorders and PTSD.  

Advocacy – We speak out for effective services which protect and support children and young people.  

Counselling – We provide a referral service to a range of specialist counselling services for children and young people to assist recovery from the impact of abuse, family violence and neglect.

Community Education – We aim to improve community education around issues of child abuse, family violence, homelessness and mental health issues. 

www.facebook.com/InternationalCommunityAdvocates

general.headline: Clinical Psychologist at Private Practice
general.description:
Natasha Lakaev is professionally registered as a Clinical Psychologist with Australian Health Regulation Practitioner Agency (AHPRA) and is a full member of the Australian Psychological Society’s (APS) College of Clinical Psychologists. She is on the APS Identified Practitioner List for treating Autism Spectrum Disorders and Pervasive Developmental Disorders and is a Medicare approved provider for Department of Veteran Affairs. Is also, a STAP certified Supervisor and approved by APS & AHPRA.

Natasha originally earned a Bachelor of Applied Science from Hawkesbury Agricultural College of Advanced Education in New South Wales (now known as University of Western Sydney) in 1986. Natasha Lakaev later pursued a Graduate Diploma in Psychology from the Queensland University of Technology in 2006. She went on to receive a Postgraduate Diploma in Psychology from Bond University in 2008, as well as a Master of Psychology (Clinical) at Charles Sturt University in 2012. 

Natasha Lakaev has demonstrated considerable research skills throughout her academic and professional career, including the development and validation of the Lakaev Academic Stress Response Scale (LASRS), a tool to effectively measure academic stress response. The results of her thesis, which focused on the LASRS, were published in the Australian Journal of Psychology and Counselling. Natasha is currently undertaking her PhD from the Department of General Practice on the impacts of Mindfulness. 

Natasha has created and presented workshops titled ‘Resolving Vilification’. The were designed to provide Professionals with the skills to prevent and/or Resolve Vilification within both private and government structures.

Ms. Lakaev currently has a private practice on the Gold Coast (QLD) and in Northern NSW, Australia. She is also a government contractor for the Access to Allied Psychological Services (ATAPS) program with North Coast (NSW) Medicare Local (NCML) and Gold Coast Medicare Local (GCML).

jobs.description:
Creation and presentation of workshops titled ‘Resolving Vilification’ in each capital city in Australia. 

Developed this Workshop into Webinar series and Online Training Course

The 2 to 4 day workshops were designed to provide Professionals or their colleagues/clients with the skills to prevent and/or Resolve Vilification (e.g., false complaints, bullying, defamation, harassment).
	
Additional provision of individual Professional Consultations to Business, Health and Education professionals that have been vilified, or that have had clients/patients vilified.

Experienced Operations Manager with extensive experience in all care groups and possess transferable skills  that are relevant to alternative health and social care settings. In my current role, I am the lead social work officer and responsible for the delivery of an effective response to social work, mental health and homelessness emergencies out with normal  working hours, covering 7 local authorities, spanning a population of 2.6 million people. Responding to child protection referrals forms a large part of the teams workload and I have excelled in this culturally diverse, multi-disciplinary and fast paced environment, ensuring the provision of expert advice whilst highlighting and encouraging innovative practice.

I have a professional commitment to continuous improvement in all aspects of service delivery. I operate best in results based environments and enjoy harnessing and aligning the competencies of the people I work with while developing individuals and teams to effect social impact and service viability. I have a personal commitment to social justice and improvement of communities through my professional practice.

jobs.jobTitle: Dell Computers Partnership Relationship Manager ANZ
jobs.description:
Role Overview
	Provide phone and face to face sales support to Dell’s national sales team on behalf of Unisys Australia. 
	Develop, manage and maintain excellent relationships with Dell management, legal counsel, sales executives and support representatives. 
	Achieve Dell sales growth of 65% year on year.
	Develop new sales and service solution initiatives to spear head Dell Services in the Australian and New Zealand markets. 
	Responsibility for the Unisys alliance with Dell Computers Australia and New Zealand. Combined with alliance reporting responsibilities to the Unisys General Manager for Asia Pacific. 
	Achieved major successes in client satisfaction with Sydney Water, Suncorp, GIO and Corplink (Queensland Government).

Channel Account Manager
Cisco Systems Australia
	
	Managing relationships with 20 Cisco partners within a sales team to achieve a team target of $600m in sales (including $10m in individual sales). Responsibility included contract negotiation and management, formulating account sales, marketing, training and business strategies, working with customers and distributors to secure opportunities and devising and implementing activities and events to enhance sales revenues.
	Coordinating resources, including engineers, Cisco management, computer based training, online training, external training and leader lead training to achieve Cisco accreditation and networking sales.

Key Achievements
	130% quarter on quarter sales revenue growth across all accounts by understanding customers’ business models and developing an matching approach, developing strong relationships with key decision makers and influencers, meeting commitments and adopting a structured and systematic approach
	Expanded annual networking sales for Dell Computers from $70k to $900k by understanding Dell’s organisational structure, sales strategies, decision makers, influencers and the company’s business development strategies and goals, researching the company’s products, identifying opportunities to extend Dell’s reach by selling Cisco products and devising and presenting sales, marketing and business plans. 
Leveraged Dells’ marketing strength, created and implemented a joint solutions marketing campaign and designed qualifying and closing scripts for sales and technical representatives. Also provided escalation processes and additional resources to resolve complex customer issues. Built strong levels of trust with Dell sales staff and management.
	Generated $1.9m in leads for Dell

Role Overview
	Establishing and managing the performance of two national teams, comprising 17 engineers, to provide technical support, training and problem resolution services for over 2,000 Cisco partners
	Increasing the product awareness and technical competency of the Cisco partner channel
	Provided back-up support and education on Cisco solutions to the company’s 20 internal sales representatives.
	Managed technical configuration camps, quarterly partner updates and Cisco University with responsibility for reviewing the learning materials and advising on the most effective delivery processes
	Coordinating and managing the delivery of 2,000 Cisco solution training courses to partner and customer engineers nationally
Key Achievements
	Established Australia’s first Technical Pre-sales Channel Partner Support team, expanding it to 18 engineers nationally, supporting over 4,000 calls a month 
	Consistently achieved customer satisfaction ratings of 4.4/5 while the business was undergoing a 50% growth rate.
	Integral contribution to a 60% close rate for all incoming calls as a direct result of the quality of the advice provided by the pre-sales team 
	Designed and implemented Cisco Asia’s first Engineering Graduate Program which became one of the three most successful within the company world-wide and has been integrated into Cisco Europe and the US. 
	Instrumental in increasing sales by 30% and significantly enhancing customer satisfaction by coaching, facilitating and coordinating the training of 2,000 engineers on Cisco products, tools and technology, coordinating Cisco Security training for the company’s channel partners and 26 configuration camps across Australia and New Zealand
	Launched Cisco’s Partner E-learning solution at the company’s premier partner event

jobs.description:
Working as part of the casual pool in all areas of the hospital including emergency department, preoperative suite, medical and surgical wards. 
The Sydney Eye Hospital is a quaternary referral unit, providing surgical and medical management of vitreo-retinal, corneal, glaucoma, oculo-plastic and oculo-oncology conditions.
Sydney Hospital and Sydney Eye Hospital functions as one hospital and is co-located on the site of Macquarie Street in Sydney's central business district. 
The Hospital includes ground floor emergency with eye hospital outpatients, two levels of clinical wards and an operating theatre on the top floor as well as an eight level car park.
Sydney Hospital has a dedicated hand unit and is a tertiary referral centre for hand trauma, abnormalities and diseases.

The Hospital also incorporates the Kirketon Road Centre and Sydney Sexual Health Centre which provide sexual health, drug and alcohol, HIV/AIDS and an AIDS psychiatry services.

Sydney Hospital and Sydney Eye Hospital has become a centre of excellence in the areas of eye, hand and sexual health as well as specialist alcohol and other drug treatment services, including such clinical areas as the Sydney Eye Hospital, Sydney Hospital Hand Clinic, Sydney Sexual Health Centre and Kirketon Road Centre.

Sydney Hospital and Sydney Eye Hospitals' modern facilities and professional staff provide a strong blend of general and specialist medical services for the public.

jobs.description:
The role of emergency departments is to care for emergencies. An emergency is when an illness or injury is serious and requires urgent attention.

The order in which you will be seen in an emergency department is determined by the seriousness of your health problem, not the time of your arrival. Those people with the most serious and urgent conditions will always be seen first, and those with less serious conditions may have to wait until the doctor is free (NSW GOV 2015)

Our fully accredited day surgeries are equipped with state-of-the-art facilities and professional staff.

Procedures are performed on a same-day basis and include, laser vision correction, cataract surgery, cosmetic surgery, removal of skin cancers, carpel tunnel surgery, hernia repairs, colonoscopies, gastroscopies, gynaecological examinations and other surgical procedures that require short or local anaesthesia.

Consultations are required with Specialists who are accredited to the day surgery unit before surgery is scheduled. Fees charged for these procedures may be covered by private health funds and Medicare.

Primary IVF are committed to providing high quality, affordable IVF to all Australians. We are the only IVF clinic that provides Medicare bulk billed IVF. Cycle fees are completely bulk billed and we will also bulk bill all ancillary services where possible (including GP consultations, pathology and radiology). The only out of pocket expenses you will incur are those not covered by Medicare, and these are generally not large amounts and may not be applicable to all patients.

Primary IVF has a team of leading IVF specialists, nurses and scientists to guide and assist patients through their IVF journey. They each have a wealth of experience in the IVF industry and are committed to excellence and positive patient outcomes.

All IVF procedures will be conducted at our state-of-the-art day surgery and laboratory, both are fully accredited and licensed.

Dutiful Daughters is a fully accredited, boutique home care provider. We have been delivering our unique brand of care and support throughout Sydney since February 2000. Our aim is to assist you to maintain your lifestyle and empower you to continue to be independent (dutifuldaughters.com.au)

After 25 years as CEO and Executive of leading health organisations in Australia, I am excited to have taken up the challenge of running my own consulting business, as CEO and Principal of Partners2Health.

I’m ready to help others to find solutions from the skills and experiences I have learnt over all that time.

I’ve worked across health and social services in diverse, complex and often geographically dispersed organisations, in both the public and private/not-for-profit sectors. My roles have spanned an unusually broad spectrum, in policy, planning, purchasing and providing services, at national, state and regional levels. 

I’ve had extensive experience in public administration and in working with governments, in positions such as Deputy Secretary of the Australian Department of Health and with a broad range of responsibilities. So I can guide you through that maze, whether it’s a CEO role, strategy and policy development, tenders, business cases, or communications and advocacy. 

I've also been:

jobs.companyName: The Society of Hospital Pharmacists of Australia
jobs.description: The Society of Hospital Pharmacists of Australia (SHPA) is the national, professional, for-purpose organisation for leading pharmacists and pharmacy technicians working across Australia’s health system, advocating for their pivotal role improving the safety and quality of medicines use. Embedded in multidisciplinary medical teams and equipped with exceptional medicines management expertise, SHPA members are progressive advocates for clinical excellence, committed to evidence-based practice and passionate about patient care.

- Mental Health Australia is the peak, national non-government organisation representing and promoting the interests of the Australian mental health sector and committed to achieving better mental health for all Australians
- I joined the Board at a time of major reform sweeping across the sector, and in particular through PHNs, arising from government acceptance of many of the recommendations of the national review which I had led and the National Commission’s report, Contributing Lives, Thriving Communities.

The National Rural Health Alliance is the peak national body for rural and remote health and wellbeing in Australia. The Alliance works to lead, unite and harness the sector’s intelligence as the national catalyst for change and innovation in rural and remote health, to improve fairness and equity for 7 million Australians living in rural and remote Australia.

The National Mental Health Commission is responsible for overviewing mental health and suicide prevention across Australia, to influence reform and to help people live contributing lives by reporting, advising and collaborating on mental health. The Commission works across all States and Territories and across all sectors - not just government and not just health services. The Federal Government tasked the Commission with undertaking a comprehensive review of Australia's mental health system, to look at its efficiency and effectiveness, overlaps and gaps in services, and what enables a contributing life. The review has now been released - it is available at http://www.mentalhealthcommission.gov.au/our-reports/review-of-mental-health-programmes-and-services.aspx

jobs.jobTitle: Deputy Secretary, head of Rural and Regional Health Australia, and Chief Allied Health Officer
jobs.description: Executive member with policy responsibility for primary and ambulatory care, population health (including tobacco plain packaging), regulatory policy and governance (including research, safety and quality) and the Australia New Zealand Therapeutic Products Agency. I was also the head of Rural and Regional Health Australia and in March 2013 I was appointed as the Commonwealth's first Chief Allied Health Officer. Following a restructuring of the Department, in late 2013 my policy responsibilities were changed to Primary and Mental Health Care, Population Health, and Indigenous and Rural Health.

As the peak national body of Australia’s divisions of general practice, comprising 111 divisions across Australia, as well as eight state-based organisations, I played a lead role in positioning the members as central to national primary health care reform and evolution of network into future Primary Health Care Organisations (PHCOs) – Medicare Locals.

jobs.companyName: Little Company of Mary Health Care
jobs.description: Little Company of Mary Health Care is one of Australia's largest private or not-for-profit health care organisations, best known for the Calvary hospitals, aged, community and home care services. Appointed as the first National CEO for the group, I was responsible for leadership and management – strategic and operational – of a diverse organisation across six States and Territories of Australia and with more than 8000 staff.  This included a major organisational change process, taking independent, diverse, and geographically dispersed services and successfully developing a single national system providing a broad range of services to the community.  This included significant expansion of the organisation through both organic growth and strategic acquisitions: in my time as National CEO, revenue increased from $175m to $750m in eight years.

I was also chair of the Australian Health Ministers Advisory Council (AHMAC), the peak advisory council to all Australian and New Zealand Ministers for Health, from March 1998 to June 2000.

Queensland Health is responsible for the planning and delivery of health services to what was then a population of 3.3 million people. As head of policy and planning, I was responsible for statewide policy development, health services planning, capital works, infrastructure and workforce planning, casemix development and implementation, private sector policy including private hospital collocations, and intergovernmental relations including negotiation of the Commonwealth/State Health Funding (Medicare) Agreements.

general.headline: Secondary Trauma Specialist Clinical Supervisor & Compassion Fatigue Educator, Keynote Speaker
general.description:
I have recently become very interested in the effects of compassion fatigue on healthcare professionals. So I became a compassion fatigue educator in order to help address this issue directly through our healthcare systems. 

There are all sorts of issues related to the overwhelm compassion fatigue creates in helping professionals. Those issues can only be addressed effectively if compassion fatigue is a part of the prescribed solutions. 

It's imperative that healthcare providers, in particular, address this phenomena and ensure it doesn't get in the way of their practice, or their working environment. 

Compassion fatigue is fast becoming a (silent) endemic across the western healthcare system and requires careful consideration along with solid, practical and immediate implementation of new skills, mindsets and approaches to healthcare delivery. 

Having just returned from the world's best conference on compassion fatigue, I'm fresh up with inspiration and the latest means for addressing this issue on our wards and in our private practices. And I want to share this information with those who need it most - frontline staff.

Having worked with people in trauma most of my career, I've found secondary trauma in helping professionals to be way more prevalent than expected. Secondary trauma is a serious issue and affects many many professionals, especially those who are experienced and competent in their work. Unfortunately, this particular stress response can be overwhelming, causing isolation from peers and those who can help. Which is why I've created a private practice where healing can commence in very private ways. 

If you're an organisation after a better means for addressing staffing issues, consider one of my workshops or individualised sessions for helping your people live and work better. 

If you're an individual and interested in compassion fatigue or think you may have secondary trauma responses going on, get in touch!

jobs.description:
Quality Clinical Supervision feels nurturing and you learn helpful stuff from it. Through C.S. your resilience develops further, you grow your understanding of yourself and your unique contribution to your discipline, your patients. 

I provide 2 pronged CS that are often interlinked:
1/ CS for helping the person in trauma
2/ CS for the professional witnessing trauma

If you're spending lots of time with people in trauma, you might benefit from specialist CS around secondary trauma. To check, consider how much you're taking your work home - does that affect your relationships, your home life, are you noticing negative changes in your lifestyle? Are you dreaming or nightmaring about what you've experienced at work? Are you finding yourself overly engaged & uncomfortable in providing the care you want to provide? Or maybe you're avoiding important stuff - like the patients, colleagues, or friends'  BBQ's? These aren't always indicators of a trauma response, but certainly impact on your own wellbeing. 

Secondary trauma is the trauma experienced by those who help people in direct trauma. It is secondary because it happened to someone else, but the helper is affected through the witnessing, the helping role they play. This is especially an issue for healthcare providers. 

If you feel the need to talk about what's happening at work, then give me a call & we can chat about your needs. And I promise not to push you, or put any hard sells on you! 

My CS technique is gentle and effective (not bullish rah-rah) and is uniquely poised to address the personal transformation that comes through trauma responses & effectively promotes resilience. 

If you'd like to know more about getting through your trauma experience - primary or secondary - get in touch and we can chat.

general.description: A simple visit to the optometrist changed my life – instead of being prescribed glasses to help me I was informed that I had a serious eye condition and that I needed to go to a specialist. From the specialist I was sent to a second specialist who then sent me to the Sydney Eye Hospital where it was confirmed that I had MD (Macular Degeneration). I was able to continue working ifor a few years after that, until my eyesight deteriorated to a point where I could no longer meet the high standard that I expected of myself. In the years to follow a did a lot of soul searching trying to come to terms with my vision loss until 2008 I found myself at a Vision Australia’s Gosford Low Vision Clinic and that’s where my life really started for the better. As a client I learnt many new things: learning to use the long cane, computer programmes and other life skills to help me with future employment. I now have a seeing eye dog named "Echo" with her by my side we can do anything we put our minds too

general.description:
B.Sc., M.B.B.S., M.Med. (Psychotherapy), FACPsychMed
MED 0001162606
ANZAP

Do you struggle on a daily basis? Does it hinder your progress in the world?

As change is an inevitable part of life we all need to find mature ways to successfully manage both the expected and unexpected adjustments to situations.

The external world can be challenging.

Yet many people also unconsciously self sabotage their own progress in career and love. They don’t allow success to be theirs.

These people are intelligent, high functioning resources who lack the insight to understand their unconscious machinations.

They often feel bewildered, fraudulent, frustrated and harshly self critical. They can feel resentful and envious towards others who do move onwards and upwards in their chosen fields. As their confidence decays symptoms of anxiety and depression can manifest. Self soothing is sought which may potentially lead to addictions.

These addictions may include: alcohol and other drugs, sex, gambling, exercise, food, internet porn, work. All expressions of self sabotage which can lead to risky self defeating cycle of abuse.

By providing a safe and discrete environment away from corporate and family scrutiny, Dr. Downey helps to create a space for reflection and exploration. He skillfully supports people to be curious as they seek out any hidden and unhelpful beliefs. These beliefs  are considered, deconstructed and, ultimately, replaced with new and more appropriate ones.

The end result of this curiosity is a personal sense of relief and freedom.

Felling more confident, vital and curious in all facets of their world, these people lead a life of maximum personal and professional success.

With a background in Medicine, Neuroscience, Psychotherapy and Meditation Dr. Downey is well positioned to assist such people and their circumstances through this journey.

His continuing professional education and supervision ensures that his clinical skills remain current.

general.headline: Parental Alienation | Resources | Research | Lived Experience Educator & Public Speaker on Parental Alienation
general.company: Parental Alienation Australia Ltd t/a Eeny Meeny Miney Mo Foundation
general.description:
My professional background is financial controlling and accounting with over 20 years experience. I have worked in various industries gaining extensive experience in gas exploration, property, not for profits, retail, wholesale, manufacturing, earthmoving, building and mining. I have also gained great experience in presenting financials, building timelines and parental contributions for more fairness in family court matters.

As a volunteer I am a lived experience educator of parental child abduction (PCA) and parental alienation (PA). I was a child of PCA and PA losing my mother to suicide as a result of the alienation. The whole experience impacted on many parts of my life as a child then later as an adult.

In Jan 2012 as a separated parent I had my own children abducted interstate. Influenced, forced to lie to professionals and manipulated into rejecting me by their other parent and stepparent. 4 years later my son secretly contacted me and we reunited in Sep 2015, he has been living with me since. Then 2 years later I started secretly meeting with my daughter after 6 years of being isolated and alienated from her.

With history repeating itself I have had extensive experience that I can now help others with, as well as help educate professionals to better understand the dynamics, tactics and impact of PCA and PA.

•	In June 2014 I started a support group for Australian based parents who are alienated from their children with approx. 1000+ members.
•	In January 2015 I founded Parental Alienation Australia Ltd t/as Eeny Meeny Miney Mo Foundation a not for profit that is registered as a health services and advancing education charity,
•	In August 2016 I started a support group for New Zealand based parents who are alienated from their children with approx 150+ members.
•	On the 12 October 2016 our organisations started the 1st Parental Alienation Awareness Day in Australia #PAADay.

general.headline: 2018 ACT Young Australian of the Year / Public Speaker /  Churchill Fellow / Social Innovation / Prince2® Practitioner
general.description:
He's been a homeless teenager, a soldier in Afghanistan, a gridiron player for Australia, a Churchill Fellow, and he was also a youth worker on call 24/7. After leaving home at 15, Zack couch surfed and spent time on the streets, before he set a goal to join the army which turned his life around. He spent tours of duty in Afghanistan before post-traumatic stress disorder saw him medically discharged. So, Zack set himself another goal – to make the Australian gridiron team within 18 months. Remarkably, he was playing in the World Cup in the United States within 17 months. He then trained as a youth worker, and was YouthCare Canberra’s first full-time outreach worker. With compassion and consistency, Zack helped teens find temporary accommodation, attend court or hospital, overcome drug addictions or transform their lives after time in jail. Zack was supporting and inspiring some of his community’s most disadvantaged and disengaged young people, this was recognised by becoming a multi award winning program.
In 2017 he was awarded a Winston Churchill Fellowship to research the " Cure Violence" approach to reducing violence within at-risk communities. Where he undertook research in Chicago, Baltimore, Detroit and Rio de Janeiro. He spent two weeks in each location living within severely underprivileged communities and working on the frontline to understand how role models are empowered to use their influence to curb violence in their communities.

general.headline: Chief Executive and Principal Commissioner at Queensland Family and Child Commission
general.description:
Cheryl Vardon is the Chief Executive and Principal Commissioner of the Queensland Family and Child Commission (QFCC). She has held the role since October 2015.

Cheryl was recently awarded an honorary doctorate (Doctor of the University) by Griffith University
She has a distinguished career as an educator and is recognised for her leadership in the protection of vulnerable children and young people. 

In 2016 and 2017 Cheryl led a series of reviews for the Queensland Government leading to practical systems reform measures to keep vulnerable children more than safe. Cheryl is an experienced reviewer of systems using case studies and stories to influence policy and establish reforms.

She has a sound track record of expertise in the implementation of complex policies into strategies and outcomes.

In previous roles Cheryl has  provided strategic analysis and advice on contested areas of public policy within highly regulated environments

Cheryl’s breadth of experience has seen her conduct assignments and provide advice in policy development and strategy review, business development, leadership mentoring and community services.

Her background includes representation of Australian governments, companies and organisations both nationally and internationally.

Cheryl’s work in Indigenous education and services for Indigenous children and young people has received a Prime Minister’s Reconciliation Award.

Cheryl has held many leadership, board and statutory roles, as a Director-General, Chief Executive, Commissioner and Adjunct Professor, in private, public and not-for-profit organisations, including education departments, children’s services departments, consumer affairs, a national charity, universities, and tribunals

She is a Fellow of the Australian Institute of Managers and Leaders, a Fellow of the Australian College of Educators, a member of the Australian Institute of Company Directors and a member (Women for Media) of the  Women's Leadership Institute Australia

general.headline: Founder and CEO at Inspired Adventures | Founder and CEO at Inspired Travel
general.description:
If you had to sum up Justine’s personal mission in one sentence, it would read: change lives and grow philanthropy through sustainable travel.

While this has always been a thread running through her life, it’s only relatively recently that all her experiences and skills have come together so that she could put it into action.

Originally from the UK, Justine began her career in sales and marketing before moving into direct marketing for IT companies such as IBM and Dell.

A chance meeting with a former Tibetan political prisoner in 2001 while she was taking a year’s leave to travel and volunteer in India, however, inspired her to change direction.

Seeking to apply her skills in direct marketing to fundraising, Justine started working at an agency that helps charities with their direct mail, telemarketing, regular donations and events programs.

She then created one of Australia’s first face-to-face fundraising agencies which, under her leadership, grew to employ 250 people and raised tens of millions of dollars for 16 leading NGOs such as Cancer Council NSW, Médecins Sans Frontières (Doctors Without Borders) and Amnesty International.

Wanting to bring travel into the fundraising mix, Justine then decided to set up an agency dedicated to empowering charities to host challenging adventures around the world, and in 2004 Inspired Adventures was born.

To date, Inspired Adventures has created and managed more than 500 adventures, each of which has raised an average of $80,000 for their charity partner, adding up to almost $30 million raised for charities and communities in need around the world.

Thanks to Justine’s vision, she and her motivated team at Inspired Adventures are changing the world, one adventure at a time.

general.headline: Co Founder & Development Director at Whitelion
general.description:
Whitelion, a national not for profit organisation was established in 1999 to provide transition services to young people (YP) exiting the justice system.  Working with these high risk youth showed Whitelion that the primary risk factors for youth offending were being placed in the Out-of-Home Care system and being homeless, leading to a broadening of services to address these factors. 

Today, Whitelion exists to give young people the pride, courage and opportunities to change their lives, aiming to increase social connection and inclusion in local communities, building meaningful relationships and creating opportunities that enable highly vulnerable young people to reach their full potential.  We believe every young person in Australia should have equal opportunities in life regardless of their circumstances. 

Whitelion provides creative solutions and programs that improve the social and economic capabilities of at-risk YP, offering a continuum of services from prevention in schools through mobile outreach, case management, mentoring, and vocational pathways.

jobs.description:
August Consulting is a boutique business consultancy with a passion for improving your business performance through practical procurement initiatives and targeted cost optimisation opportunities.

We believe that increasingly complex business challenges demand the deployment of key people with deeper expertise to influence change and enable a more robust outcome delivery focus.

Our points of difference are our ability to translate complexity into clear roadmaps and deliverables ready for execution. We are a team of experienced people who are genuinely passionate about working with you to achieve success.

In simple terms, we operate with integrity to actually deliver excellence. 

www.augustconsulting.com.au

Led a significant reform within Queensland Heath’s procurement service, moving from operational to strategic focus with a 5-year plan to meet customers' needs. Transformation delivered an improved service, significant commercial benefits ($200M over 5 years) whilst ensuring continuity of supply. 

Focussed on execution.  Ensured clear vision, purpose and operational plan to deliver on agreed outcomes. Utilised agile methodology to ensure momentum and a culture of success.

Implemented key enablers to provide a platform for success, including capability uplift, governance frameworks, regular communications and customer reporting. 

Oversaw the development of a robust benefit measurement framework to report on measurable benefits. Introduced regular reporting and data analytical tools to increase visibility of performance and drive customer engagement.

Established a shared service procurement function ($300M), including grassroots approach to developing a procurement function, providing category management, within an agreed governance framework, delivering measurable benefits for internal service groups. 

Robust business case was approved, demonstrating over $12M savings over 5 years. Post implementation review initiated by the board reported successful implementation and proposed benefits being realised.

Created vision, strategy and supporting business plan to lead the establishment of a new department. Led procurement team restructure, including developing supporting job descriptions to build a centre-led procurement operating model.

Advised on and participated in negotiation panel for a $30M ICT outsourcing deal. Negotiated contract to ensure service improvements on current service and network availability, including productivity improvements, benchmarking provisions, service levels and credits related to KPIs.

Led successful implementation of Helping Out Families service ($30M) within Beenleigh, Eagleby and Nerang in line with Department of Communities, Service Agreement within agreed budget and timeframes. 

Implemented a project governance framework and reporting to support successful project tracking and implementation.

Established partnerships with the private sector for the delivery of additional services to the NHS providing greater choice and reduced waiting times for patients. 

Contract Manager for Independent Sector Extended Choice Network (£85M), covering 11 providers providing acute services to the NHS and for the Home Oxygen Service (£110M) managing 3 independent sector providers, servicing 87,000 patients across 152 Primary Care Trusts.

Resolved complex contractual disputes, achieving savings of £5M per annum. Gained ministerial approval on a £17M contract settlement, avoiding mediation. 

Managed the Home Oxygen Supply Service (£110M) in England, including working with private sector to achieve agreed KPIs to support service delivery excellence, drive innovation and improved patient outcomes. Worked to deliver a strategic review on the service. The review included wide engagement with the NHS, healthcare professionals and external stakeholders (British Lung Foundation, British Thoracic Society) which delivered a number of key recommendations that were integral to the future development of the service, including procurement and policy drivers.

general.headline: Leasing Lawyer - Senior Associate at MinterEllison
general.description:
I am a leading leasing lawyer, specialising in all facets of leasing with a focus on managing large retail shopping centre portfolios on behalf of institutional landlords as well as overseeing a strong cross-jurisdictional tenant practice nationally.  

My commercial and pragmatic approach to lease negotiations focuses on building a long-term partnership between landlords and tenants, resulting in optimal outcomes for clients and the community. 

I am known in the retail leasing space for streamlining leasing process by adopting innovative practices, technology and process improvement as well as championing the adoption of national plain-English leases.

I am currently a member of the Property Council's Retail Committee and regularly present to my peers and the broader community on topical leasing issues on behalf of MinterEllison, Property Council of Australia Academy, Queensland Law Society and Legalwise. 

I welcome you to contact me directly at tanya.sciasci@minterellison.com.

jobs.description:
In my role at MinterEllison I oversee leasing assets for a number of market leading entities including Charter Hall, Queensland Investment Corporation, AMP, Fortius, Lendlease, Suncorp and Challenger.

I have a focus on retail leasing, with my current remit including in excess of 40 retail shopping centres in Queensland and northern New South Wales. 

I also act for Suncorp nationally across its retail, commercial and industrial portfolio. 

Highlights of my time at MinterEllison so far include: 

* Developing the new national plain English retail lease in conjunction with Charter Hall - reducing the existing lease precedent by half!  
* Negotiating Suncorp's iconic Pitt Street Mall Discovery Store
* Partnering with Lendlease in its Urban Regeneration project at the RNA Showgrounds
* Working with QIC from day 1 of their partnership with MinterEllison Queensland

At McCullough Robertson I passionately drive a national leasing practice for both landlords and tenants across a diverse range of asset classes. 

I pride myself on streamlining large transactions by bringing together a multi-disciplined, cross jurisdictional team to achieve the best outcome for my client with a focus on harnessing technology and legal innovation to maximise accuracy and efficiency. 

I also have a particular interest in retail leasing and during the consultative process for the proposed amendments to the Retail Shop Leases Act 1994, made submissions to the Department of Justice on behalf of both McCullough Robertson and key client stakeholders.

I am a regular presenter to clients and the industry with recent topics including: 

•	Hypothetical Panel – The minefield of multi-use development sites (QLS Property Symposium 2016)
•	Knocking down the walls – Redevelopment and demolition provisions under the Retail Shop Leases Act 1994 (Qld) (Legalwise - June 2016)

general.headline: Lawyer | Editor In Chief at The Legal Forecast | Events Coordinator at Pride in Law
general.description:
I view myself as a development lawyer assisting with planning, property and environment matters.  My environmental science degree enables me to understand environmental legislation and policy at a higher level compared to some lawyers.

If you have met me, you likely know my mantra is for everyone to “live out loud”.  As an openly gay lawyer, I co-founded McCullough Robertson’s LGBTI+ initiative, McColour.  I also currently sit as the Events Coordinator for Pride in Law, Australia’s first LGBTI+ legal networking association.  I am passionate about LGBTI+ inclusion in the legal industry because I have been told my sexuality would hold back my career along with other demeaning comments.  I will never stop fighting to prove them wrong.

My passion for a more just society includes several other causes.  I co-founded Australia's first university club aimed at preventing gender-based violence: Griffith Mentors in Violence Prevention.  I also assisted with creating the first bills ever to reform abortion laws in Queensland and co-founded Young Queenslanders for the Right to Choose.  I volunteer several hours every month to the Homeless Persons’ Legal Clinic because the impacts of poverty should never be criminalised.  I have worked with The Legal Forecast for years to increase access to justice through innovation and technology.

So that’s enough about “Biddy”, please feel free to message me.  I am always keen for a coffee catch up anytime to discuss any of the above and hear more about you.
