jobs.description: Disputes & Investigations, Restructuring and Insolvency

8 - 12 hours per week 

In this role, I have routinely been tasked with conducting research for a client's legal issue in a wide area of practices ranging from Defamation to Tax to International Trade Law. 

In one instance, I assisted a food importation company based in Australia resolve a legal dispute with suppliers in India by conducting research into the rules of contract as stipulated in the United Nations Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods (Vienna, 1980).

The experience has taught me a lot about the role of civil procedure in Queensland and many of the formal processes required to resolve legal disputes between clients. In particular, I have been involved in constructing statements of claims, defence statements as well as providing written advice to clients and opposing solicitors outlining the dispute and our legal position.

20-35 hours per week

Working at the Apple Store in Brisbane's CBD, I have been involved in a range of environments that have provided me with unique career experiences. 

I often found myself using the resources around me to solve complex customer issues as they arose, having to adapt to these new scenarios within a fast-paced environment. 

As a Specialist, I supported both retail operations and the business team by connecting them with new business customers. Being the first person that new business customers would meet, I helped the business team understand the business needs by asking relevant questions and then providing the right solutions. Through these business interactions, I gained skills in communicating in a professional, but still very personal way.

In supporting retail operations, I provided amazing customer experiences by translating technology talk into everyday language that could be understood by anyone. These experiences allowed me to build strong relationships with customers, discover their needs and then provide complete solutions, whilst operating under Apple's strict confidentiality agreements. 

I have assisted with the launch of key products through the composure I bring to busy environments and the willingness to help out where needed.

These skills along with my passion for training new team members led to being named a Mentor for the store. In my role as a Mentor, I was responsible for checking in with new staff, reinforcing training materials and acted as a point of reference for technical and customer issues. 

I have participated in many zones within the store having presented workshops to tutor newcomers to Apple's technology, provided technical support to resolve customer issues as an Apple Qualified iOS technician and consistently produced results in my position. 

Throughout my time at Apple, I was open to feedback from both my peers and managers as it allowed me to grow as a team member and improve workflow.

jobs.description:
LawGraduate Coach assists law students and junior lawyers to demonstrate their unique skills and develop fulfilling career strategies. Discover how to promote your skills to a firm that is perfect for you, your goals and ambitions.  

As an experienced Graduate Recruiter, Tanya Dunbabin knows what top tiers through to boutique law firms are looking for, assisting you to stand out in a crowded marketplace. With 20 years experience in law, and the last 7 years managing the Graduate Recruitment Program at Herbert Smith Freehills, Tanya can assist to navigate the various pathways that present themselves to you, from job seeking in the early years of university through to developing as a high performing lawyer.  Tanya can offer support in your search for a casual paralegal role through to vacation clerkship applications, excelling in a clerkship, starting as a graduate and developing as a junior lawyer.  Personalised coaching and career guidance can build strength as you embark on your career, developing from a high performing graduate, to an outstanding lawyer.  

Building a career ladder takes time - it steps sideways as well as upwards. At times it involves Plan A, but others it involves Plan B.  Navigating confidence, showing initiative, eagerness and resilience all hinge on a tightrope - often tipping one way or another.  Tanya’s coaching approach can assist to set up your early career choices to develop a brand you are proud of, developing the attributes required to be a high performing graduate and junior lawyer.  

Tanya works to shine a light on your unique attributes, matching your personality & goals to a firm that’s right to support you. With experience in clerkship, graduate and lateral recruitment, rotation planning, matching supervisors & graduates, & performance development, Tanya can work with you to realise & enhance your potential. Tanya focuses on discovering who you are & how your offering sets you apart in a profession that expects only the best.

general.headline: Senior Construction Lawyer at McCullough Robertson
general.description:
A construction and engineering claims specialist, Bill advises in all aspects of construction disputes involving litigation, arbitration and alternative dispute resolution processes.
 
Bill has extensive experience litigating in the nation’s Supreme and Federal Courts.  He specialises in contract administration and works with project managers to achieve project objectives and to manage out the risk of protracted disputation.
 
He acts for principals, owners, contractors, superintendents, subcontractors, manufacturers, suppliers and consultants (including architects and project managers) in both the government and private sectors.
 
His public sector advisory work includes regularly advising Government Regulatory bodies about amendments to the legislative regime governing the building and construction industry.  Private sector clients include those in mining, heavy manufacturing and infrastructure, where he advises on construction and engineering disputes.
 
Recent experience includes:
 • contractual advice for Mackay Sugar on construction of a renewable biomass Cogeneration Plant
• acting for Roche against Anglo in a dispute in relation to Sunrise Gold Mine in Western Australia
• acting for QANTAS against Mulitplex concerning the design and construction of heavy maintenance facilities at Brisbane Airport
• acting for Stork ICM against Krupp Uhde in a dispute in relation to the ammonium nitrate plant at Moura
• international arbitration in Mexico over the construction of an oil refinery and pipeline, and
• acting for Devine Limited in relation to construction claims brought by contractors.
 
He has had first hand involvement with the Building and Construction Industry Payments Act 2004 (BCIPA) for Authorised Nominating Authorities, claimants and respondents at all stages.  He has also lectured extensively on this topic to construction industry participants.

general.headline: Partner at McCullough Robertson
general.description:
Mick is a workplace relations specialist with particular expertise in industrial relations negotiations, bargaining and dispute resolution in the construction, resources and State Government sectors. 

He also advises clients from a range of other industries, including the electricity, manufacturing and transport sectors, on a full range of employment related matters including contractual drafting and interpretation, discipline and termination issues.

A summary of some of Mick’s experience includes:

• advising owners and contractors on a number of large infrastructure and industrial projects on the appropriate industrial relations strategies and frameworks for those projects

• directly negotiating enterprise bargaining agreements and other business solutions with the coal mining union for a number of major coal mining contractors

• representing mine owners and contractors in seeking orders against industrial action

• advising clients on executive remuneration and termination issues

• advising clients on restraint of trade and confidentiality disputes

• advising clients on business restructures and takeovers including managing the redundancy process and all legal issues surrounding termination of employment and transfer of entitlements

• successfully representing a major airline in an unfair dismissal claim and also in a claim by the international pilots’ union to extend its coverage to the airline’s domestic flight crew.

general.headline: Senior Associate (Construction) at Corrs Chambers Westgarth
general.description:
I am a construction dispute resolution lawyer, and a Senior Associate at Corrs Chambers Westgarth.  

I advise owners, contractors, suppliers and government bodies about the avoidance, strategic management and resolution of construction disputes.
 
I have been involved in the conduct and successful resolution of disputes on a range of civil, mechanical, commercial and resources projects throughout Australia.  
 
I work alongside my clients to assist them with their contract administration and the preparation and defence of contractual claims, including claims for variations, latent conditions, extensions of time, delay and disruption costs and liquidated damages.  
 
I also represent clients in all forms of dispute resolution, including:

-  arbitration 
-  expert determination, and
